snippet.textDisplay:
Hello doctor Mike, I want some advice as a student. Since you are a DOCTOR, that's indicative of how much you had to study or still study. And You also find time for YouTube with your hectic work schedule. Considering these similarities. I wanted to ask you for some advice.

I am preparing for a very competitive exam in my Country which also has a lot of syllabus to cover and books to read from. It takes years to successfully crack the exam. It would really help to know

1)how to manage to study so much,
2)cope with unexpected time loss, distraction, moods,
3)coping up with sacrificing other activities, hobbies and outtings etc. And still maintain peace of mind.

I usually stick to my schedule but sometimes I find myself lost in thoughts of how's life going to be cause I don't know if I'll make it through the exam or not. If I'll ever be able to do all the bucket list items I have planned to do in the future.

it usually gets triggered by seeing someone's social media post of something they did Or some video or just disappointment or worry over incomplete tasks.

I know people suggest staying away from social media or YouTube etc but I study by myself at home and I can't find other ways of recreation when bored. I do art sometimes but even that skill is rusted these days with all the overthinking.

I hope this helps to understand my situation.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hello Dr. Mike or anyone else reading this.

It’s almost impossible for someone so famous as Dr. Mike to hear my story but I hope that it reaches you. This isn’t really my story, more of my moms, but I can share my experience. My mother really needs medical advice!

And here is begins. About 2-3 years ago my mother, father and I visited San Diego. My mother was walking on the beach and then fell. She cried out in pain so we rushed her back to our hotel room. She didn’t want medical attention even though we insisted. A couple days later we were back home and she finally agreed to go to the doctor because she was still in pain. The doctor said my mother had torn her right legs tendon. My mother told the doctor that it felt like she was shot in the leg, that’s how bad the pain was. Now we are back in present time and my mother’s leg feels better. Yet now she is suffering from extreme lower back and nerve pain. My aunt is a physical therapist so my mom goes to her at least three times a week. My mother’s back pain was so bad that she had to have a back surgery. The surgery helped. But not as much as we hoped. Her doctor says the pain is probably from when she tore her tendon. But we don’t know for sure. So now her doctor is giving her the option of having a fusion. I would really appreciate if in one of your upcoming videos you could speak about lower back pain and causes and solutions. And possibly if a fusion is the way to go. This was really hard to write and tell because I am only 13 and don’t have much experience. But I really want my mom to feel better, and it breaks my heart that she can hardly move. She is always in pain and she doesn’t deserve it. 😭❤️.
